<td><a href="UltraBoard.cgi?Action=ShowProfile&ID=venti&Board=ranger&Idle=30&Sort=0&Order=Descend&Page=0Session&Session=" target="Profile" OnMouseOver="window.status='View Venti (venti) Profile.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Profile</font></a><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 "> | </font><a href="mailto:jr68@ispchannel.com" OnMouseOver="window.status='Send email to Venti.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Email</font></a></td><td align="RIGHT"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="EEEEEE">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">In the post prior to mine, the player indicates that he can not solo green fawns in NK.  WHY??  I was soloing them when they were blue (formidable) to me.  The problem may be the same as I have seen many other rangers, and other classes in fact error in.  You must use all the tools available to you.  In the case of the blue fawns, I would snare, and dd them with 50% of my mana, and while still kiting, throw arrows at it mainly just to increase my archery skill.  At the end of the kiting when snare wears off, go to melee.  Prior to the initiation of the fight though, you must be sure to self buff wood, cat and thistles.  Many a time I have had to zone with the job incomplete because I forgot to buff up first.<p>

The balance of my mana is used for healing.  Although, if the mob gets into you for more than half your health, you should be binding wound first to conserve mana.<p>

The point here is that your Ranger is capable of a whole lot more than just tanking the crap out of a mob.  I see alot of characters of all classes play their game and only use 50-75% of their capability.  Think the fight out before you engage, and remember to begin with the end in mind.<p>

What I enjoy the most about being a Ranger is that it is not just a melee character.  I retired a monk and a warrior because it was boring to me to just be a meat shield.  <p>

Even with all the difficulties in playing a ranger, he is my favorite.  Let's face it, if you pull with snare, and melee, you will find that it takes a lot to get the mob off of you, and on to the main tank in your group.  All the while, you feel the effect of having lower AC and hit points than a real heavy tank (warrior/pali/monk).  Because snare is a long lasting effect on the mob, you stay high on his hate list, especially if you are attacking as well as the presence of the snare.  I don't think Verant needs to fix this with adding a pet or charm pet ability, in my opinion, a succssful Ranger will know his limits, and constraints, and strengths, and play to them accordingly, because there are other things we get that balance the "deficiencies".<p>

All of this is of course, simply my opinion, and not meant to indicate that I know anything more than the next guy, but rather just my slant on life as a Ranger.<p>

Best to all,<br>
Venti<br>
26th Ranger<br>
Master fletcher<br>
Master smith<br>
friend to all rangers</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
