<td><a href="UltraBoard.cgi?Action=ShowProfile&ID=krys&Board=ranger&Idle=30&Sort=0&Order=Descend&Page=0Session&Session=" target="Profile" OnMouseOver="window.status='View Krys (krys) Profile.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Profile</font></a></td><td align="RIGHT"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="EEEEEE">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Up 'til about level 23 or 25 or so, I took pride in taunting off other tanks 5 levels higher than me.  It was a source of pride, and since the ac/hp gap wasn't that big at those levels, didn't really hurt the group.  I strongly suggest playing around with "how fast can I taunt the mob off of a taunting warrior?" at those levels.<p>

As I got higher in levels, I began seeing the desparity in taunting that the gap in AC/hps created.  I looked for ways to do exactly the opposite.  It wasn't until about level 35 or so that I actually found a tank that could out taunt me when I wasn't tryint to taunt.<p>

Secrets to taunting well:  cast long lasting spells, and cast them right away.  Nothing taunts faster than the first Snare or DoT.  In the begining of combat, before the mob has taken too many hits or taunts, the two spells that are pretty much guaranteed to agro the mob onto you are snare and flame lick (yeah, that lvl 9 spell.. I still carry around a fire beatle eye).<br>
Be the puller.  Pulling gives you a chance to be the only one on the agro list, and will build a pedistal for you that the other tanks and casters have to tear down.  If you want to stay up there, pull with snare and shoot lots of arrows at it.<br>
Hit harder and faster than anyone else.  Use duel wield with a couple low delay weapons.  Procing weapons are real nice for this also.<p>

Secrets for avoiding the agro:  It's ok to pull, but avoid using snare at all costs.  If you have to pull, get a SoW first and don't snare to pull.  If you have to cast, use your DD spell (DoTs agro much more than DDs do).  If you don't have access to the SoW spell, snaring may be the only option.  If this is the case, snare, bring back, root, back off.  Let the tanks take a few seconds to get the mob on them.  Sitting there taking a beating still causes them to agro you.<br>
Drop a damage shield on the main tank.  The damage is done by the main tank, and therefore adds agro to his list, and makes yours not as bad.<br>
If at all possible, don't attack when you pull.  Walk up to them and let them attack you, then run away.  This will cause the least amount of agro on you and let the main tank start taking damage sooner.<br>
During multiple pull situations, don't stand next to the unagroed mobs.  They'll more than likely be attacking the closest person to them, and you don't want that person to be you.<p>

Playing the enchanter:  yes, we can do crowd control, just not nearly as well as enchanters can.  Cast root on an undamaged non-casting mob and move EVERYONE away.  This includes pets and tanks.  Works best in open areas and with a group that will listen to directions.  Will also help in agroing a mob off of a healer (or at the very least let the healer move away from the mob)<p>

Tip to pulling well: avoid agro at all costs, and the good puller will bring in 1 or 2 mobs tops (damn monks with their FD advantage, but it stunts the skill factor)<p>

Comments on previous posts:<p>

rangers are the most dificult class to play?  Granted, it's not easy, but the Enchanter class is right up there (have 31 'chantress also).<p>

monks as a tanking class?  please, their HP and AC is right down their with ours.  Their advantage is their high damage output (none higher in melee classes save for rogues).  Save the damage for the Warriors, SKs and Pallies.<p>

Krys, lvl 38 ranger</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
