<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Pulling/tanking continued<p>

At first, I always pulled with Snare, and took me a while to figure out why I was usually never able to have another player taunt the mob off me.  Since then, I have changed strategy, and share it for your review.  I will still pull, and if multiples, use my harmony spell to single pull as it seems to never get resisted.  I'll throw an arrow at the target mob, and pull back to the group.  I will self buff skin like rock, but NOT thistlecoat, and will not snare at this point.  When the mob is brought to the group, the appropriate warrior will taunt off, and normal fighting resumes.  When mob has been damaged sufficiently, I will cast snare, unless a druid has already done so, and this is really only so I dont have to chase mob when it runs.<p>

Reasons for this strategy:<br>
1)  If you cast Snare, the mob has you at the top of it's hate list, right away.<br>
2)  Thistlecoat is not used, beacuse every time the mob hits you, it takes on damage as a result, keeping you at the top of the hate list, and making the mob nearly untauntable.<br>
3)  Rangers have excellent stats for Dex and Agi, which make you land more of your hits, and able to defend better against mob's blows.<br>
Because of our high skill in dodge/parry/defense, this seems to be working for me.<p>

In closing,<br>
As I see it, yes, by not buffing with thistle, i do lose 5-6 AC, but because I am not the constant object of his "affection" I take less damage overall.  Imagine the mob getting madder and madder at you everytime it lands a blow, because it scrapes his knuckles against your thistles......<p>

Just my 2cp worth<p>

Venti<br>
26 Ranger</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
